{{Infobox member of the Knesset |image = Uriel Lin.jpg |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1935|4|2|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Jerusalem]], [[Mandatory Palestine]] |death_date = |death_place = |Knesset(s) = [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|11]], [[Israeli legislative election, 1988|12]] |party1 = [[Likud]] |partyyears1 = 1984–1992 }}
'''Uriel Lynn''' ({{lang-he|אוריאל לין}}, born 2 April 1935) is an [[Israel]]i lawyer, former civil servant and politician. Currently president of the Federation of the Israeli Chambers of Commerce and the Tel Aviv and Central Israel Chamber of Commerce, he served as a member of the [[Knesset]] for [[Likud]] between 1984 and 1992.
==Biography== Lynn was born '''Uriel Asulin''' in [[Jerusalem]] during the [[Mandatory Palestine|Mandate era]]. His father, Yehonatan Asulin was from [[Morocco]], while his mother, Margalit Hazan, was born in Palestine. His grandfather, rabbi Ben-Zion Mordechai Hazan, was one of the founders of the [[Porat Yosef Yeshiva]] in [[Jerusalem]], and officially handed over the [[Old City (Jerusalem)|Old City]] of Jerusalem to the Jordanians during the Israeli surrender there in the [[1948 Arab-Israeli War]]. Lynn attended the Nautical School in [[Haifa]]. He served in the [[7th Armored Brigade (Israel)|7th Armored Brigade]] of the [[Israel Defense Forces]], and fought as a reservist in the [[Suez Crisis]], [[Six-Day War]], and [[Yom Kippur War]]. and afterwards studied law at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] and [[University of California, Berkeley]],<ref name=P>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=484 Uriel Lynn: Particulars] Knesset website</ref> earning an LLM from both universities. He was certified as a lawyer devoting two years in litigation of cases related to traffic accidents and from 1965 until 1970 worked as secretary and legal advisor at the ATA textile company.<ref name=PA>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=484 Uriel Lynn: Public activities] Knesset website</ref>
Between 1969 and 1971 he worked as deputy general manager at Isranyl, a textile factory, which later on was transformed to Jerusalem Jersey Textile where he continued working as managing director between 1972 and 1979.<ref name=PA/>
In 1973 Lynn joined the [[Liberal Party (Israel)|Liberal Party]], which was part of the [[Likud]] alliance. He was placed 56th on the Likud list for the [[Israeli legislative election, 1977|1977 Knesset elections]],<ref>[http://en.idi.org.il/media/513522/%D7%9B%D7%A0%D7%A1%D7%AA%209-%20%D7%94%D7%9C%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%93.pdf Likud list (1977)] Israel Democracy Institute</ref> but failed to win a seat. In 1978, following Likud's election victory, Lynn became a civil servant after being appointed Director of the North American Investment Authority. In 1982 he became Director General of the [[Ministry of National Infrastructures, Energy and Water Resources|Ministry of Energy and Infrastructure]].<ref name=PA/>
In [[Israeli legislative election, 1984|1984]] Lynn was elected to the Knesset on the Likud list. He was appointed chairman of the Subcommittee on Energy and of the Subcommittee for Road Safety, and also chaired the Parliamentary Inquiry Committee for Traffic Accidents.<ref name=KA>[https://www.knesset.gov.il/mk/eng/mk_eng.asp?mk_individual_id_t=484 Uriel Lynn: Knesset activities] Knesset website</ref>
He was re-elected in the [[Israeli legislative election, 1988|1988 elections]] after being placed 23rd on the Likud list.<ref>[http://en.idi.org.il/media/512130/%D7%9B%D7%A0%D7%A1%D7%AA%2012-%20%D7%94%D7%9C%D7%99%D7%9B%D7%95%D7%93.pdf Likud list (1988)] Israel Democracy Institute</ref> In his second term in the Knesset he chaired the Constitution, Law and Justice Committee till 1992.<ref name=KA/>
In 1992 he decided not to run again as candidate to the Israeli Knesset, and established again his own law firm,<ref name=PA/> specializing in arbitration and government.
At the end of 2002 he was elected President of the Tel Aviv & Central Israel Chamber of Commerce and of the Federation of Israeli Chambers of Commerce. He also became a member of the board of the [[Eurochambres]] and was elected a member of the council of the World Chambers Federation (WCF), a worldwide organization of National Chambers of Commerce.
